componentInstanceProperties.value:
Below is a list of things that the AMT and customer MUST be aware of before this is done. ID Cards would go out in the normal course of maintenance. It could take up to 3 business days for the new ALTID to be available in all downstream systems.

 

• The member may have to re-register on myuhc

• The member would not be able to use their current card

• If medical claims come in with the old ALT ID there could be denials

• Any medical auths, care coordination, UBH auths, etc. may have to be redone or transferred, if applicable

• Any RX auths, mail order, etc. may have to be redone or transferred,if applicable, PLEASE CHECK WITH RX IN ADVANCE

• There could be issues with HRA, if applicable

• Any feeds to CAMS would need to be addressed in advance, if applicable

• Vision and Dental would need to know in advance to point out any potential impact, if applicable

• There could be issues with any vendor feeds we send out if they use our ALT ID, they would need to approve, if applicable

• The change is immediate so all historical coverages would be impacted and not just the most recent coverages

 

In addition, the changing of the ALT ID may NOT actually stop a fraudulent claim (if one were to come in) from being processed on TOPS. The ALT ID points to the EEID (SSN). If we assign a new ALT ID then the old ALTID and the new ALT ID will both point to the same EEID. TOPS may process the claims whether it comes in with the new ALTID or the old ALT ID.

 

The only way to truly stop any fraud is to assign a new EEID number. That means the group would have to use that number forever (instead of the social) when they communicate to us on this member. That would probably impact any other vendors they deal with as well as their HR system. This could have an impact on financial products(FSA, HRA, etc.) if applicable.
